'''Virender Sehwag''' {{audio|Virender_Sehwag.ogg|pronunciation}} ({{lang-hi|<U+0935><U+0940><U+0930><U+0947><U+0902><U+0926><U+094D><U+0930> <U+0938><U+0947><U+0939><U+0935><U+093E><U+0917>}}) (born 20 October 1978), affectionately known as ''Viru'', the ''Nawab of Najafgarh'', or the ''Zen master of modern cricket'',<ref>{{cite web
|author=Mukul Kesavan
|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/485985.html 
|title=Cricket's modern Zen master
|publisher=espncricinfo.com 
|date=8 November 2010
|accessdate=22 November 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|author=Mukul Kesavan
|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1101107/jsp/opinion/story_13145845.jsp
|title=THE ZEN MASTER: <U+2013> Sehwag or the art of concentration maintenance
|work=The Telegraph |location=Kolkota, India 
|date=7 November 2010
|accessdate=22 November 2010 }}</ref> is one of the leading [[batsman|batsmen]] in the [[Indian cricket team]]. Sehwag is an aggressive right-handed opening batsman and a part-time right-arm off-spin bowler. He played his first [[One Day International]] in 1999 and joined the Indian [[Test cricket]] team in 2001. In April 2009, Sehwag became the only Indian to be honoured as the [[Wisden Leading Cricketer in the World]] for his performance in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|author=TNN, 9 April 2009, 12:16&nbsp;am IST |url=http://cricket.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/4377189.cms |title=Sehwag is world's top cricketer for 2008 |publisher=Cricket.timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=9 April 2009 |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> subsequently becoming the first player of any nationality to retain the award for 2009.<ref name=WisdenLC>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisden.com/default.aspx?id=2|title=Wisden Leading Cricketer In The World|accessdate=14 April 2010|publisher=Wisden}}</ref>

Sehwag created history when he crossed the 200 run mark in ODI's on 8th December, 2011 at  Indore. He scored 219 off 149 balls against the West Indies during the 4th ODI of the 5 match series, with a strike rate of 146.97. His score of 219 is the highest score in ODI's. In typical Sehwag fashion, he reached the 200 run mark with a 4. Sehwag has formed a habit of reaching milestones with boundaries.   	

Sehwag holds multiple records including the highest score made by an Indian in Test cricket (319), which was also the fastest triple [[century (cricket)|century]] in the history of international cricket (reached 300 off only 278 balls) as well as the fastest 250 by any batsman (in 207 balls against Sri Lanka on 3 December 2009 at the [[Brabourne Stadium]] in Mumbai). His other innings of 309 and 293 are also the second and third best by any Indian player. Sehwag also holds the distinction of being one of four batsmen in the world to have ever surpassed 300 twice in Test cricket, and the only one to score two triple centuries and take a five-wicket [[innings]] haul.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/india/content/current/player/35263.html |title=Player profile Cricinfo |publisher=Content.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> In March 2009, Sehwag smashed the fastest century ever scored by an Indian in ODI cricket, from 60 balls.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mathrubhumi.org/news.php?id=13501&cat=1&sub=17&subit=0 |title= PTI: Sehwag becomes fastest Indian centurion in ODIs |date=11 March 2009|work=Mathrubhumi  |accessdate=12 February 2010 }}</ref> On 8 December 2011, he hit his maiden double century in ODI cricket, against [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], becoming the second batsman after [[Sachin Tendulkar]] to reach the landmark.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ind vs WI: Sehwag slams 112-ball 150 as India eye massive total|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/series-tournaments/west-indies-in-india/top-stories/Ind-vs-WI-Sehwag-slams-112-ball-150-as-India-eye-massive-total/articleshow/11031022.cms|accessdate=8 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=8 December 2011}}</ref> He holds the current record for the highest individual score of 219 off just 149 balls in ODIs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virender Sehwag slams maiden double century in ODIs, scripts history|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/series-tournaments/west-indies-in-india/top-stories/Virender-Sehwag-slams-maiden-double-century-in-ODIs-scripts-history/articleshow/11033211.cms|accessdate=8 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=8 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Virender Sehwag becomes 2nd batsman to slam 200 in ODIs|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/wi-ind-2011/news/item/182104-4th-odi-sehwag-becomes-2nd-batsman-to-slam-200-in-odis?pfrom=home-lateststories|accessdate=8 December 2011|newspaper=[[NDTV]]|date=8 December 2011}}</ref>

Sehwag was appointed as vice-captain of the Indian team under [[Rahul Dravid]] in October 2005 but due to poor form, he was later replaced by [[V. V. S. Laxman]] in December 2006 as Test vice-captain. In January 2007, Sehwag was dropped from the ODI team and later from the Test team as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/indvwi/content/story/276198.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag out, Ganguly picked for ODIs |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> During his term as vice-captain, Sehwag skippered the team in place of injured Dravid in 2 ODIs and 1 Test. Following his return to form in 2008 and the retirement of [[Anil Kumble]], Sehwag has been reappointed as the vice-captain for both Tests and ODIs. By early 2009, Sehwag had reestablished himself as one of the best performing batsmen in ODI cricket.<ref>{{cite web|author=Cricketnext.com |url=http://cricketnext.in.com/news/top-performer-virender-sehwag/38979-25.html |title=Cricketnext: Top Performer: Virender Sehwag |publisher=Cricketnext.in.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>

==Early years==
Sehwag was born in a [[Jat]] family from [[Haryana]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040416/edit.htm#8|publisher=''[http://www.tribuneindia.com/ The Tribune]''|title=Verma<U+2019>s gift for Sehwag|author=Tribune News Service 
|date=16 April 2004|accessdate=16 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20021019/windows/main1.htm|publisher=''[http://www.tribuneindia.com/ The Tribune]''|title=Top shot|author=Tribune News Service 
|date=19 October 2002|accessdate=11 February 2006}}</ref><ref name="Virender Sehwag Jat">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Nawab-of-Najafgarh-their-hero-Jat-boys-pad-up-for-a-long-innings/articleshow/4257471.cms|title=<U+2018>Nawab of Najafgarh their hero, Jat boys pad up for a long innings
|last=Pushkarna|first=Neha|date=13 March 2009|work=The Times of India |location=India|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref> The son of a grain merchant, Sehwag spent his childhood in a bungalow in a [[joint family]], with siblings, uncles, aunts and sixteen cousins. Though now settled in New Delhi, the Sehwag family hails from Haryana. Sehwag was the third of four children born to father Krishan and mother Krishna Sehwag, with two older sisters Manju and Anju, and younger brother Vinod. His father attributes his interest in cricket to a toy bat which he was given when he was seven months old. He attended Arora Vidya School in Delhi, and pestered his parents to let him play cricket, on the basis that he was not academically gifted.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://clients.rediff.com/philipseyefi/Virender.htm |title=rediff.com World Cup 2003: An encounter with Virender Sehwag's family |publisher=Clients.rediff.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}{{dead link|date=September 2011}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> His father tried to end his career when he broke a tooth as a child in 1990, but Sehwag evaded the ban with the help of his mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040403/windows/main1.htm |title=Super Sehwag |work=The Tribune |location=India |date=3 April 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2010 }}</ref> Later he attended [[Jamia Milia Islamia]] for graduation.

==Cricketing career==
===Early domestic cricket===
Sehwag made his debut for [[Delhi cricket team]] in first class cricket in the 1997<U+2013>98 season. He was selected to the [[North Zone cricket team]] for the [[Duleep Trophy]] the following 1998<U+2013>99 season, ending fifth in the total runscoring list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1998-99/IND_LOCAL/DULEEP/STATS/IND_LOCAL_DULEEP_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html |title=Batting <U+2013> Most Runs |publisher=.cricinfo.com |date=17 June 2008 |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> The following year he was fourth on the Duleep Trophy run scoring list, including a 274, the highest score of the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1999-2000/IND_LOCAL/DULEEP/STATS/IND_LOCAL_DULEEP_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html |title=Batting <U+2013> Most Runs |publisher=.cricinfo.com |date=17 June 2008 |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> This was attained against [[South Zone cricket team|South Zone]] at [[Agartala]] in just 327 balls, and followed a rapid 187 from just 175 in a Ranji Trophy match against [[Punjab cricket team|Punjab]].<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/95850.html |first=Anand |last=Vasu |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Give Sehwag the freedom to run riot |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |date=3 August 2001 |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> He was then selected for the U-19 team which toured South Africa.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> He was seventh in the 2000<U+2013>01 season with two centuries,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2000-01/IND_LOCAL/DULEEP/STATS/IND_LOCAL_DULEEP_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html |title=Batting <U+2013> Most Runs |publisher=cricinfo.com |date=17 June 2008 |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> but his consistency earned the attention of selectors and he became a regular member of the national team in mid 2001.

Since his international career started, he has continued to play for Delhi in the domestic competition whilst he is not occupied with international duty and has captained North Zone to victory in the [[Deodhar Trophy]] in 2004<U+2013>05 and 2005<U+2013>-06.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/NATIONAL/IND/DEODHAR_WINNERS.html |title=India <U+2013> Deodhar Trophy Winners |publisher=Cricinfo |date=17 June 2008 |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> He also had a short stint with [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]] in county cricket in 2003, but a back injury lead to a mutual termination of the contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/129053.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Leicestershire and Sehwag part company |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>

=== ODI career ===
Sehwag's [[One Day International|ODI]] career started poorly when he scored 1 against [[Pakistani cricket team|Pakistan]] in [[Mohali]] in April 1999 when he fell lbw to [[Shoaib Akhtar]]. His bowling performance was also ineffective and expensive, conceding 35 runs off 3 overs. He did not get another chance in the national team for 20 months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1998-99/OD_TOURNEYS/PC-IND/SCORECARDS/IND_PAK_PC-IND_ODI6_01APR1999.html |title=6th ODI: India v Pakistan at Mohali, 1 Apr 1999 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>
[[Image:Indiancricketers.jpg|thumb|upright|Sehwag with teammates [[Harbhajan Singh]] (Left) and [[Yuvraj Singh]] (Middle).]]
Sehwag was not given another match until the home series against [[Zimbabwean cricket team|Zimbabwe]]{{ref|ODIALL}} in December 2000. Sehwag rose to prominence in his fourth ODI match in March 2001 when he scored 58 off 54 balls, against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]] in [[Bangalore]]. Combined with his three wickets, he help earn India a victory and was awarded his first man of the match award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2000-01/AUS_IN_IND/SCORECARDS/AUS_IND_ODI1_25MAR2001.html |title=1st ODI: India v Australia at Bangalore, 25 Mar 2001 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> He followed this with an unproductive tour of Zimbabwe in mid 2001.

Sehwag had his international breakthrough in [[Sri Lanka]] in August 2001 when he was promoted to the opening slot for the tri-series also involving New Zealand. The promotion to open the innings came because regular opener [[Sachin Tendulkar]] was absent due to a foot injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/india/content/story/101381.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Injured Tendulkar ruled out for Sri Lanka tri-series |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> In the match against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]] that was to decide the finalist, he scored his maiden century from 69 balls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2001/OD_TOURNEYS/CCC-SL/SCORECARDS/IND_NZ_CCC-SL_ODI9_02AUG2001.html |title=9th Match: India v New Zealand at Colombo, 2 Aug 2001 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> At the time, the century was the third fastest ODI century for an Indian behind [[Mohammad Azharuddin]]'s 62 ball effort and Yuvraj singh's 64 ball effort. This was his first score beyond 50 in ten matches and saw him named man of the match. This performance earned him a regular spot in the ODI squad in the middle-order. He bettered his own record by hitting a 60-ball century against New Zealand during the 2009 tour. An innings of note in 2002 was the 22 ball half-century against [[Kenyan cricket team|Kenya]] in [[Goodyear Park|Bloemfontein]], tying the second fastest 50 by an Indian. Because of his attacking cricket stroke plays, Sehwag has got many fans, including the WestIndies legend Desmond Haynes, who admitted that he is a great fan of him.<ref>[http://www.crickipedia.com/news/I_am_a_Sehwag_fan__says_Desmond_Haynes.html]{{dead link|date=September 2011}} {{dead link|date=September 2010}}</ref>

With Ganguly's injury in the India-England ODI Series in January 2002, Sehwag received another opportunity to open the innings which he seized by scoring 82 from 64 balls in [[Kanpur]] in an eight-wicket Indian victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2001-02/ENG_IN_IND/SCORECARDS/ENG_IND_ODI4_28JAN2002.html |title=4th ODI: India v England at Kanpur, 28 Jan 2002 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> With good performances as opener, Sehwag was made a permanent fixture at the top of the innings. [[Sachin Tendulkar]], who opened in the England ODI series, was moved to middle order<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/119988.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Pushing Tendulkar and Dravid around |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> <U+2013> a strategy that reaped dividends for [[Indian cricket team|India]] in 2002 in ODI matches. In the England series and the preceding tour to South Africa, he compiled 426 runs at 42.6 with four half-centuries {{ref|ODIALL}}.

After modest returns on the tours of the West Indies and England in early and mid 2002, he scored 271 runs at 90.33 in the [[2002 ICC Champions Trophy]] in Sri Lanka, with two man of the match performances. After running out [[Ian Blackwell]], he was involved in a 192 run partnership with Ganguly, scoring 126 from 104 balls to help set up an eight wicket victory against England in a group match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/OD_TOURNEYS/ICCCT/SCORECARDS/POOL2/ENG_IND_ICCCT_ODI11_22SEP2002.html |title=England v India at Colombo (RPS), 22 Sep 2002 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> He then scored 58 from 54 balls and took 3/25 including two wickets in the final over to help defeat [[South African cricket team|South Africa]] by 10 runs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/OD_TOURNEYS/ICCCT/SCORECARDS/KNOCKOUTS/IND_RSA_ICCCT_ODI-SEMI1_25SEP2002.html |title=India v South Africa at Colombo (RPS), 25 Sep 2002 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> to help India progress to the final.

In late 2002 he scored an unbeaten 114 from 82 balls that included a 196 run partnership with Ganguly to lead India to a nine wicket win over the West Indies in [[Rajkot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/WI_IN_IND/SCORECARDS/WI_IND_ODI3_12NOV2002.html |title=3rd ODI: India v West Indies at Rajkot, 12 Nov 2002 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> He was the only batsman to score a century in the 7 match [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]] ODI Series where he made two centuries <U+2013> 108 in Napier<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/IND_IN_NZ/SCORECARDS/IND_NZ_ODI2_29DEC2002.html |title=2nd ODI: New Zealand v India at Napier, 29 Dec 2002 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> in an Indian defeat and 112 in Auckland<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/IND_IN_NZ/SCORECARDS/IND_NZ_ODI6_11JAN2003.html |title=6th ODI: New Zealand v India at Auckland, 11 Jan 2003 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> in a one-wicket victory.

Virender Sehwag had a mediocre [[2003 Cricket World Cup]], scoring 299 runs at an average of 27, he top scored with 82 in the loss against Australia in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/WORLD_CUPS/WC2003/SCORECARDS/FINALS/AUS_IND_WC2003_ODI-FINAL_23MAR2003.html |title=Final: Australia v India at Johannesburg, 23 Mar 2003 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> 
[[Image:Virender Sehwag fielding.jpg|thumb|left|Sehwag in fielding practice.]]
Later in 2003, he scored his fourth century and earned Man of the Match award against New Zealand in [[Hyderabad (India)|Hyderabad]], scoring 130 and putting on a 182 run partnership with Tendulkar, to lay the foundations for a 145 run victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/OD_TOURNEYS/TVS/SCORECARDS/IND_NZ_TVS_ODI9_15NOV2003.html |title=9th Match: India v New Zealand at Hyderabad, 15 Nov 2003 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> In spite of it, Sehwag struggled for consistency in 2003 and 2003/04 ODI series where he had only one century and 3 fifties, two against minnows <U+2013> [[Bangladesh cricket team|Bangladesh]] and [[Zimbabwe cricket team|Zimbabwe]] and one against [[Pakistani cricket team|Pakistan]], in 22 matches.

Even with his inconsistent form, he earned 3 MoM awards in 2004/5 and 2004/05 ODI season with one award each against Sri Lanka, Bangladesh and Pakistan. In the match against Pakistan in [[Kochi, India|Kochi]] he scored 108 off 95 balls, his first century in eighteen months which set up a 95 run victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2004-05/PAK_IN_IND/SCORECARDS/PAK_IND_ODI1_02APR2005.html |title=1st ODI: India v Pakistan at Kochi, 2 Apr 2005 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> 

Sehwag then started a two year streak without a century in ODIs, as well as having his ODI tour of Pakistan in early 2006 curtailed due to a shoulder injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/236855.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag and Harbhajan to return home |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> His drought in limited overs cricket has puzzled cricket experts because of the consistent performances in [[Test Cricket|Test matches]] with a high scoring rate has not translated into significant contributions in the ODI format of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/223060.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag<U+2019>s one-day blues |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> Sehwag was dropped from the ODI Squad for the [[West Indian cricket team in India in 2006-07|WI-IND 4 Match ODI series]]. With debate over whether he deserved to be included in the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]] squad, captain [[Rahul Dravid|Dravid's]] insistence on his retention paved the way to being named in the World Cup squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/243385.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> India to persist with Sehwag at the top |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> However, despite this assurance, Sehwag's form continued to decline. 

Sehwag started the 2007 World Cup in poor form, only being picked for the side because of Rahul Dravid's wishes. He scored poorly in the first group match but bounced back to hit a magnificent 114 from 87 deliveries against lowly ranked Bermuda. The Indian team scored 413<U+2013>5, the highest team total in a World Cup match, and went on to win the match but this was their only win in the tournament.

On 11 March 2009, Sehwag blasted India's fastest ODI hundred against New Zealand by reaching 3 figures in just 60 balls. Eventually, he led India to win its first series win in New Zealand.

In [[2011]], Sehwag scored his highest ODI score against [[West Indies]] at [[Indore]].

===ODI summary ===
Sehwag's scoring rate is extremely quick, at 103.44 runs per 100 balls (it is exceeded only by one current player: Shahid Afridi, who has a much lower average). He has had more success in run chases, scoring seven of his thirteen centuries while chasing. He has led India on seven occasions, due to the unavailability of the incumbent due to illness, injury or rotation policy. In [[December]] 2011 Sehwag scored 219 in 149 deliveries against [[West Indies]] at [[Indore]]. He has the record of highest individual score in [[ODI]].

=== Test career ===
[[Image:Virender Sehwag Graph.png|right|thumb|350px|An innings-by-innings breakdown of Sehwag's Test match batting career, showing runs scored (red bars) and the average of the last ten innings (blue line).]]

Sehwag's maiden century in mid-2001 in Sri Lanka was not enough to gain selection in the Test team for the corresponding series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/95805.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag's century not enough for place in Test squad |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> Sehwag made his Test debut in late 2001 in the First Test against [[South African cricket team|South Africa]] in [[Bloemfontein]] as a middle-order batsman. He scored 105 on debut despite the South African win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2001-02/IND_IN_RSA/SCORECARDS/IND_RSA_T1_03-07NOV2001.html |title=1st Test: South Africa v India at Bloemfontein, 3<U+2013>7 Nov 2001 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> He was given a one match suspension by ICC match referee [[Mike Denness]] for overappealing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/108118.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Fines and bans handed down to Indian players |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> in the Second Test in [[Port Elizabeth]], which lead to political dispute amongst the ICC and the two countries. He returned for the home series in 2001<U+2013>02 against [[English cricket team|England]] and [[Zimbabwe cricket team|Zimbabwe]]. After scoring two half-centuries in the preceding series, he was promoted to a makeshift-opener on the 2002 England tour after the failure of previous openers and an experiment with wicket-keeper [[Deep Dasgupta]]. He scored 84 in the new role at [[Lord's]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-www1.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/117162.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Late wickets lift England after India threaten to cut loose |publisher=Content-www1.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> and then a century in the Second Test at [[Trent Bridge]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002/IND_IN_ENG/SCORECARDS/IND_ENG_T2_08-12AUG2002.html |title=2nd Test: England v India at Nottingham, 8<U+2013>12 Aug 2002 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> and has batted there in Test matches ever since. He scored his maiden home-century of 147 in the First Test against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] in the 2002<U+2013>03 home season in [[Mumbai]], which was at the time his top score in Test matches, earning him his first man of the match award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-www1.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/122042.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag century dominates West Indians at Mumbai |publisher=Content-www1.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref> After a poor tour to New Zealand, he scored passed 50 for the first time in 9 innings when he scored 130 in a Test at [[Mohali]] against New Zealand in late 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-www1.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/132948.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag's century lights up Mohali |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/NZ_IN_IND/SCORECARDS/NZ_IND_T2_16-20OCT2003.html |title=2nd Test: India v New Zealand at Mohali, 16<U+2013>20 Oct 2003 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> {{ref|TESTALL}}.

He then scored 195 against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]] on [[Boxing Day]] 2003 at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/126120.html |title=Sehwag century puts India in command |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref> His dismissal on the first afternoon lead to an Indian collapse and eventual defeat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-www1.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/126209.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Not rolled over |publisher=Content-www1.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> 

In early 2004, he became the only Indian to score a triple century in Test cricket, with 309 against [[Pakistani cricket team|Pakistan]] in the First Test in [[Multan]], beating [[V. V. S. Laxman]]'s previous Indian record(281 against Australia) and helping India to a total of 5/675, the highest ever against Pakistan. It was Sehwag's sixth Test century in 21 Tests.<ref name="Sehwag66">Armstrong (2006), p. 212.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/140466.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> India high on Sehwag's 309 |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> India went on to win by an innings, with Sehwag named man of the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/IND_IN_PAK/SCORECARDS/IND_PAK_T1_28MAR-01APR2004.html |title=1st Test: Pakistan v India at Multan, 28 Mar <U+2013> 1 Apr 2004 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> He also scored 90 in the Second Test defeat in [[Lahore]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/IND_IN_PAK/SCORECARDS/IND_PAK_T2_05-09APR2004.html |title=2nd Test: Pakistan v India at Lahore, 5<U+2013>9 Apr 2004 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> and was named man of the series for his efforts after being the highest run scorer and average for the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/IND_IN_PAK/SCORECARDS/IND_PAK_T3_13-17APR2004.html |title=3rd Test: Pakistan v India at Rawalpindi, 13<U+2013>17 Apr 2004 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/IND_IN_PAK/STATS/IND_IN_PAK_MAR-APR2004_TEST_AVS.html |title=India in Pakistan, 2003<U+2013>04 Test Series Averages |publisher=Cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> He later auctioned the bat with which he made the triple century, for Rs. 70,000, to aid in relief efforts for the [[tsunami]] victims of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake]].<ref>[http://cricketershistory.blogspot.com/2008/06/virender-sehwag.html]</ref>

In the First Test of the 2004 [[Border Gavaskar Trophy]] in [[Bangalore]], Sehwag was fined for showing "serious dissent" towards umpire [[Billy Bowden]] following an LBW dismissal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/142323.html |title=Sehwag fined 65% of match fee for dissent |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref> Replays showed that he had hit the ball off the middle of his bat onto his leg, which later led to an apology from Bowden.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/142352.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Bowden apologises for horror decision |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>
Sehwag scored 155 in the [[Chennai]] test match to set up a triple figure lead for the Indians, but the match was rained out on the final day with the Indians requiring 229 for victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/142441.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> India ride on Sehwag hundred after Warne's record |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64100.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> 2nd Test: India v Australia at Chennai, Oct 14<U+2013>18, 2004 |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> In the home series against South Africa that year, he scored 164 in the drawn First Test in [[Kanpur]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-www1.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/141890.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag shines on a sluggish pitch |publisher=Content-www1.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> and 88 in the Second in [[Kolkata]], which India won to claim the series. Sehwag was again named man of the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64110.html |title=South Africa in India Test Series <U+2013> 2nd Test. India v South Africa.  * Test no. 1724 &#124; 2004/05 season * Played at Eden Gardens, Kolkata * 28,29,30 November, 1,2 December 2004 (5-day match)

 |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>

Sehwag failed on the tour of Bangladesh, but on the 2005 home series against Pakistan, he scored 173 in [[Mohali]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64125.html |title=Cricinfo - 1st Test: India v Pakistan at Mohali, Mar 8<U+2013>12, 2005|publisher=Content-uk.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> 81 in [[Kolkata]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64126.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> 2nd Test: India v Pakistan at Kolkata, Mar&nbsp;16<U+2013>20, 2005 |publisher=Content-uk.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> and then 201 in [[Bangalore]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64127.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> 3rd Test: India v Pakistan at Bangalore, Mar 24<U+2013>28, 2005 |publisher=Content-uk.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> totalling 544 runs at an average of 90.66 to win the man of the series award. He passed the 3000 run mark in Tests during the Bangalore Test, becoming the fastest Indian to reach the mark in terms of innings played.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/146472.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Fastest Indian to 3000 runs |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> His performances over the preceding 12 months earned him selection in the ICC Test Team of the Year as well as nomination for Test player of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/219236.html |title=Player of the Year nominees announced |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref>

He earned selection for the ICC World XI which played Australia in the [[2005 ICC Super Series]], where he top scored in the first innings with 76. He attracted some criticism at the end of 2005, having failed to pass 50 in four Tests against Zimbabwe and Sri Lanka. He also missed the Second Test against Sri Lanka in [[Delhi]] due to illness,<ref>[http://wwwc1.cricinfo.com/indvsl/content/story/229012.html Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag likely to miss second Test<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref> but returned to the team in the following match in [[Ahmedabad]] and captained the Indians to victory whilst [[Rahul Dravid]] was ill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/230485.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> 'We're enjoying our cricket', says Sehwag |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>

[[File:Virender Sehwag bowling 2.jpg|thumb|Sehwag bowling in the nets.]]

Sehwag scored his first century in a year when he compiled 254 against Pakistan in the First Test in [[Lahore]] in January 2006, the highest ever Test score at a strike rate of over 100 and the second fastest double century ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/pakvind/content/story/233199.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag and Dravid pummel Pakistan |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> In doing so he was involved in a 410 run partnership with captain Rahul Dravid, the highest ever against Pakistan and in Pakistan, and just four short of a new world record opening partnership in Test matches.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/232916.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Boundary avalanches and scoring rates |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> Sehwag went on to lampoon the Pakistani attack led by [[Shoaib Akhtar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/pakvind/content/story/233296.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> 'Shoaib hasn't lived up to expectations' <U+2013> Sehwag |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> Sehwag however failed to pass 50 in the following two Tests against Pakistan, and aside from a 76* in the Second Test in [[Mohali]] against England, fell seven times for less than 20 runs to the new ball {{ref|TESTALL}}, leading criticism of his position in the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/241326.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Driving with two flat tyres |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>

During the 2006 West Indies tour, Sehwag narrowly missed out on scoring a century in the opening session of the Second Test in [[St Lucia]], ending with 99 at the interval.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/250138.html |title=Sehwag's early blast |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref> He went on to compile 180 in just 190 balls, and also collected four wickets for the match to be named man of the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-www1.cricinfo.com/wivind/engine/match/239921.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> 2nd Test: West Indies v India at Gros Islet, Jun 10<U+2013>14, 2006 |publisher=Content-www1.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> Although Sehwag had collected more than 50 wickets in ODIs, he was substantially used as a Test bowler for the first time on the West Indies tour, taking nine wickets in the first two Test matches when he was used in the absence of off-spinner [[Harbhajan Singh]] as India opted to only use one specialist spinner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/250256.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag puts his spin on it |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> He had previously only three wickets at Test level {{ref|TESTSER}}. He was also fined in the First Test for excessive appealing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/249874.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag fined for excessive appealing |publisher=Content-aus.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>

Poor form saw Sehwag being dropped from the Test team in 2007. In December 2007, he was recalled for India's tour of Australia after being omitted form the list of probables,<ref>
