==Achievements==
===Awards===
* [[Arjuna Award]] (2002)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-www.cricinfo.com/india/content/story/125215.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Sehwag 'thrilled' at getting Arjuna Award |publisher=Content-www.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>

* [[Wisden Leading Cricketer in the World]] 2008, 2009<ref name=WisdenLC/>
* [[ICC Test Player of the Year]] 2010<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/player/35263.html Virender Sehwag | India Cricket | Cricket Players and Officials | ESPN Cricinfo<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
* [[Padma Shree]] 2010<ref>[http://www.hindustantimes.com/Padma-Bhushan-for-Aamir-Padma-Shri-for-Sehwag/Article1-501571.aspx Padma Bhushan for Aamir, Padma Shri for Sehwag - Hindustan Times<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

===Records===
*Highest individual score in an ODI match 219 against [[West Indies]] on 8th December 2011 at [[Indore]].
* Fastest 250 in Test cricket in terms of balls faced (207).
* Fastest 300 in Test cricket in terms of balls faced (278).
* Most Test runs in a single day by an Indian. Sehwag made 257 in a day against SA in Chennai. He surpassed this in making 284 in a day against Sri Lanka. The latter was the second consecutive innings in which India scored more than 400 runs in a single day in Tests. Sehwag also made a century at faster than a run a ball on the previous occasion.
* Only Indian batsman to have scored two triple centuries in Test cricket. He is one of the four batsman in the history of Test cricket to score two triple centuries, alongside Australia's [[Sir Donald Bradman]], and the West Indies' [[Brian Lara]] and [[Chris Gayle]].
* Fastest century in ODI cricket by an Indian <U+2013> 100 runs off 60 balls against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]] in 2009.
* Second fastest ODI 50 by an Indian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284095.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Records <U+2013> One-Day Internationals <U+2013> Fastest fifties |publisher=Stats.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> <U+2013> a record, he shares with [[Rahul Dravid]], [[Kapil Dev]] and [[Yuvraj Singh]] <U+2013> when he took 22 balls against [[Kenyan cricket team|Kenya]] in 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/66106.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> 9th Match: India v Kenya at Paarl, October 24, 2001 |publisher=Content-uk.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>
* Six double centuries <U+2013> the first three of which came against Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/stats/index.html?class=1;filter=advanced;opposition=7;orderby=runs;runsmin1=200;runsval1=runs;template=results;type=batting |title=Cricinfo Statsguru <U+2013> Test matches <U+2013> Batting records |publisher=Stats.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2010}}</ref> [[Greg Chappell]] and [[Thilan Samaraweera]] are the other players to have scored multiple double centuries against Pakistan (2). Sehwag and Tendulkar are the only Indians to have made six Test double centuries.<ref>{{Cite news|date=12 October 2010|title=Sachin Tendulkar emulates Sehwag|work=ESPN Star|url=http://www.espnstar.com/cricket/international-cricket/news/detail/item513211/Sachin-Tendulkar-emulates-Sehwag/|accessdate=13 October 2010}}</ref>
* Highest score by an Indian batsman in Test cricket. He first achieved this when he scored 309 against Pakistan in Multan in 2004, and bettered his previous record in March 2008 at Chennai against South Africa by scoring 319.
* Fastest triple century: His second triple century scored at [[Chennai]] on 27<U+2013>28 March 2008 against South Africa was the fastest in terms of balls faced by any batsman (off 278 balls).
* Consecutive 150+ scores in Test cricket: He holds the record for consecutive test hundreds converted to scores of 150+, at 11.
* He is one of the only five players to have scored more test hundreds than test fifties (15c/14f), along with [[Don Bradman]] (29c/13f), [[Mohammad Azharuddin]] (22c/21f),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/227046.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Records <U+2013> Test matches <U+2013> Most hundreds in a career |publisher=Stats.cricinfo.com |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref>  [[Matthew Hayden]] (30c/27f) and [[Kevin Pietersen]](13c/11f)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/19296.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Players and Officials <U+2013> Kevin Pietersen |publisher=Content-www.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref> as on 7 August 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/india/content/player/35263.html |title=Cricinfo <U+2013> Players and Officials <U+2013> Virender Sehwag |publisher=Content-www.cricinfo.com |accessdate=12 February 2012 }}</ref>
* Two consecutive double century partnerships in a Test innings. He achieved this record, for the first two wickets in [[Chennai]] on 27<U+2013>28 March 2008 (with [[Wasim Jaffer]] and [[Rahul Dravid]] respectively). This was the first time in Test history that the first two wickets in an innings have resulted in double-century stands. He equalled this in the innings against Sri Lanka in Mumbai, combining with [[Murali Vijay]] and Dravid for the first and second wickets.
*  He is the first person in the history of test cricket to hit two triple centuries and take five wickets in a Test innings.
* He has launched all five of India's innings in [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011 World Cup]] to date by hitting the first ball for four. The suffering bowlers (so far) were [[Shafiul Islam]], [[James Anderson (cricketer)|Jimmy Anderson]], [[Boyd Rankin]], [[Mudassar Bukhari]] and [[Dale Steyn]].

